During normal circulation, deoxygenated blood returns to the heart via veins and is pumped to the lungs for oxygenation. The pulmonary artery carries deoxygenated blood from the right ventricle to the lungs—this is the only vessel delivering blood *to* the lung capillaries where gas exchange occurs. Therefore, even though the blood has just exited the heart, it remains deoxygenated until reaching the alveoli. At any point prior to oxygenation, whether pre- or post-stress, the pulmonary artery contains the lowest oxygen concentration because it transports un-oxygenated blood destined for gas exchange. No other listed location delivers deoxygenated blood directly from the heart to the lungs like the pulmonary artery does.

